.SH "NAME"
newgrp \- change to a new primary group
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.HP \w'\fBnewgrp\fR\ 'u
\fBnewgrp\fR [\-l] [\fIgroup\fR] [\fIcommand\fR\ [\fIargs\fR...]]
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.PP
\fBnewgrp\fR
starts a new shell environment under a new primary group\&.
.PP
If the
\fB\-l\fR
flag is given as first argument, the user\*(Aqs environment will be reinitialized as though the user had logged in, otherwise the current environment, including current working directory, remains unchanged\&. For Linux compatibility, the flag
\fB\-\fR
is allowed as well\&.
.PP
\fBnewgrp\fR
changes the current primary group to the named group, or to the default group listed in /etc/passwd if no group name is given\&. The user\*(Aqs standard shell is started, called as login shell if the
\fB\-l\fR
or
\fB\-\fR
flag has been specified\&.
.PP
The group argument can be specified as group name from the group database or a non\-negative numeric group ID\&.
.PP
If a group has been given as argument, a command and its arguments can be specified on the command line\&. Note that this usage is Cygwin\-only and incompatible with POSIX and Linux\&.
.PP
The new primary group must be either the old primary group, or it must be part of the supplementary group list\&. Setting the primary group to an arbitrary group is not allowed in Windows\&.
